    "body": "**Description of the problem**\r\n\r\nNot a bug per se - more like a misleading error message when calling a module with a single option it can't digest.\r\n\r\n**Full script that generated the error**\r\n\r\nWanted a list of the usable fonts and instead of `gmt text -L` I wrote `gmt plot -L`. \r\n\r\n```\r\ngmt plot -L\r\n```\r\n\r\n**Full error message**\r\n```\r\ngmt [ERROR]: Shared GMT module not found: plot\r\n\r\nERROR: No module named plot was found.  This could mean one of four cases:\r\n  1. There actually is no such module; please check your spelling.\r\n  2. You used a modern mode module name while running in GMT classic mode.\r\n  3. Module exists in the GMT supplemental library, but the library could not be found.\r\n  4. Module exists in a GMT custom library, but none was specified via GMT_CUSTOM_LIBS.\r\nShared libraries must be in standard system paths or set via environmental parameter LD_LIBRARY_PATH.\r\n```\r\n\r\n**Actual outcome**\r\n\r\nSaying something about the module `plot` not found which I found a bit misleading. \r\n\r\n**Expected outcome**\r\n\r\nSay something along the lines that a user shouldn't use a module with options it can't digest. Same behaviour with `coast -R`, `text -T`, etc.\r\n\r\n**System information**\r\n\r\n* Operating system: Linux\r\n* GMT version (`gmt --version`): 6.2.0_a6980cb_2021.04.28\r\n",
